Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
Today I voted to terminate the emergency declaration put in place to justify higher tariffs on Canadian imports. While not all Canadian trade practices are fair, I‚Äôm keenly aware of the negative impacts in store for Alaskan families and businesses should tariffs drive up the costs of essential goods.  

In Alaska, this relationship matters. We share more than 1,538 miles of border with Canada ‚Äì some of our communities share schools and churches. Our best-known road is the Alcan (Alaska-Canada) Highway. We are friends, neighbors, partners, and allies when it comes to our economies, our mutual defense, our cultures, and, yes, our trade. 

Like any relationship, there are certainly areas for improvement. I support the President‚Äôs efforts to block the flow of fentanyl in our country, but we should remember the old saying that the U.S. and Canada are ‚Äòneighbors by geography, and friends by choice.‚Äô In that same spirit, I‚Äôm certain we can find a better way to mutually secure our borders and address fentanyl trafficking than by starting a trade war.

text:
Yesterday, nine Republicans teamed up with Democrats to take down a procedural rule to bring both the SAVE Act (which would bolster election integrity by requiring proof of U.S. citizenship to register to vote) and the No Rogue Rulings Act (which would combat judicial activism by limiting the power of district judges to impose nationwide injunctions) to the House floor for a vote.

Why? Because they want new parents, both mothers and fathers, in the House to be able to vote by proxy.

Folks, proxy voting is unconstitutional in all cases whatsoever; Congress has a constitutional mandate to assemble. 

Moreover, we‚Äôve already seen how this unconstitutional practice can be abused. Under Speaker Pelosi‚Äôs reign, members in both parties took advantage of proxy voting while their constituents were subjected to draconian COVID policies.

The misguided action of these nine Republicans has delayed our ability to continue advancing President Trump‚Äôs commonsense policies to get our country back on track.

Running for office is a choice and being elected to serve the people is a privilege. Now is not the time for theatrics or distractions. We must refocus on what the American people sent us here to do: Deliver on President Trump‚Äôs America First agenda.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
3/ You see, our founders created a President with limited and checked powers. They specifically put the power of spending and taxation in the hands of the legislature. 

Why? Because they watched how kings and despots used spending and taxes to control their subjects.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
4/ British kings used taxation to reward loyalty and punish dissent. 

Our own revolution was spurred by the King‚Äôs use of heavy taxation of the colonies to punish our push for self governance. 

The King‚Äôs message was simple: stop protesting and I‚Äôll stop taxing.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
5/ Trump knows that he can weaken (and maybe destroy) democracy by using spending and taxation in the same way. 

He is using access to government funds to bully universities, law firms and state and local governments into loyalty pledges.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 6/ Healthy democracies rely on an independent legal profession to maintain the rule of law, independent universities to guard objective truth and provide forums for dissent to authority, and independent state/local government to counterbalance a powerful federal government.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
7/ But the private sector also plays a rule to protect democracy. Independent industry has power.

The tariffs are Trump‚Äôs tool to erode that independence. Now, one by one, every industry or company will need to pledge loyalty to Trump in order to get sanctions relief.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
8/ What could Trump demand as part of a quiet loyalty pledge? 

Public shows of support from executives for all his economic policy. Contributions to his political efforts. Promises to police employees‚Äô support for his political opposition.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
9/ The tariffs are DESIGNED to create economic hardship. Why? So that Trump has a straight face rationale for releasing them, business by business or industry by industry. 

As he adjusts or grants relief, it‚Äôs a win-win: the economy improves and dissent disappears.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
10/ And once Trump has the lawyers, colleges and industry under his thumb, it becomes very hard for the opposition to have any viable space to maneuver. 

Trump didn‚Äôt invent this strategy. It‚Äôs the playbook for democratically elected leaders who want to stay in power forever.

Name: Massie, Thomas
text:
In this episode of in-the-weeds, I‚Äôll talk about how the Rules Committee, a.k.a. the Speaker‚Äôs committee, can circumvent House rules and even federal laws that govern House rules.

There are House rules and federal laws that allow rank and file members in specific circumstances to bring legislation to the floor without the Speaker‚Äôs approval. But the Speaker can use the rules committee to ‚Äúturn off‚Äù these special procedures, if he can get a majority of members of the whole House to vote for the Rules Committee Resolution to disable these special procedures.

Let‚Äôs look at three methods for expediting legislation, that the Speaker can thwart if he can pass a tailored resolution on the floor from the Rules Committee.

1. Discharge Petition
If a member can get 218 colleagues to sign a discharge petition, legislation can be brought to the floor against the Speaker‚Äôs wishes. I‚Äôve only seen this done a couple of times in the twelve years I‚Äôve served in Congress. It‚Äôs rare because it‚Äôs considered an act of rebellion by majority members against the Speaker. It was once used to pass a bill reauthorizing the Import/Export Bank ostensibly without the approval of Speaker Boehner, but Boehner had announced his resignation and was a weak at the time.

This week, Rep Luna, in an act of defiance against Speaker Johnson, employed a discharge petition to expedite consideration of Democrat legislation to allow new mothers in Congress to vote remotely. She acquired the requisite 218 votes by enlisting all democrats and a few Republican colleagues.

The Rules Committee offered a resolution to ‚Äúturn off‚Äù the House rule that enabled her discharge petition. The resolution also contained procedures for bringing popular Republican bills to the floor that dealt with election integrity and rogue judges. The Speaker gambled that Republicans wouldn‚Äôt vote against a resolution that enabled these popular bills. I voted FOR the Soeaker‚Äôs resolution to disable the discharge petition because I agree with the Speaker‚Äôs attempt to prevent what I consider to be unconstitutional legislation from coming to the floor, and (b) the resolution modified house rules, instead of thwarting the intent of standing federal law.

The Resolution from the Rules committee failed because nine republicans joined Rep Luna and all democrats in voting against the Rules Committee Resolution that would have disabled Luna‚Äôs discharge petition. They set up a game of chicken, and the cars crashed into each other.

Unless the Speaker has more tricks up his sleeve, next week we vote on the Democrat legislation to give a sort of maternity leave to members of Congress.

2. War Powers Act

The War Powers Act sets forth an expedited procedure for Congress to countermand the Executive branch when the Executive conducts acts of war without congressional authorization. According to FEDERAL LAW, any member can bring this resolution to the floor quickly. In the past, Speakers have successfully used a Rules Committee resolution (passed by the whole House) to stop a vote on the issue of war from coming to the House floor. How can federal law be thwarted by a House Resolution? The Rules Committee merely has to say in its resolution that the war powers resolution brought forth by the member doesn‚Äôt qualify as a war powers resolution (even if it clearly does!). When I served on the Rules Committee last Congress, I made it clear that I would not engage in this nonsense, and I did not.

3. National Emergencies Act
Members can force votes to countermand Executive declarations of National emergencies, such as the one underpinning Trump‚Äôs tariffs. This was tried a couple of weeks ago, but the Speaker thwarted federal law with a Rules Committee Resolution. I was the only Republican to vote against the Speaker‚Äôs resolution, so his measure carried and we had no vote on the national emergency that underpins Trump‚Äôs new tariffs.

*written on an iphone*

Name: Collins, Susan M.
text:
Yesterday, I spoke from the Senate floor in support of the effort to overturn the emergency declaration for the northern border that has been used to impose tariffs on goods imported from Canada.

While I share the President‚Äôs goal of stemming the tide of dangerous fentanyl that flows into the United States, the fact is, the vast majority of the fentanyl in America comes from the southern border. In fiscal year 2024, less than 1% of fentanyl seizures occurred at our northern border, and the Canadians are working cooperatively with our government to stop that trafficking. Unlike Mexico and China, Canada is not complicit in this crisis.

The State of Maine‚Äôs economy is deeply integrated with Canada, our most important trading partner. From home heating oil, gasoline, and other petroleum products, to Maine‚Äôs paper mills, forest products businesses, agricultural producers, fishermen, and lobstermen, the tariffs on Canada would be detrimental to Maine families and our local economies.

The price hikes that will affect Mainers‚Äîfrom the grocery store, to filling their gas and heating oil tanks‚Äîwill be so harmful. And as price hikes always do, they will hurt those the most who can afford them the least.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
@RepDannyDavis and I have teamed up to introduce the SSI Savings Penalty Elimination Act‚Äîa bipartisan, bicameral bill that brings the first major update in 40+ years to the Supplemental Security Income (SSI) program.

Right now, outdated SSI rules punish low-income seniors and people with disabilities for saving responsibly‚Äîforcing them to choose between building a better future and keeping the benefits they depend on.

We‚Äôre fixing that. 

Our bill:

‚úÖ Raises asset limits from $2,000 to $10,000 for individuals
‚úÖ Raises limits from $3,000 to $20,000 for married couples
‚úÖ Indexes these limits to inflation permanently

It‚Äôs time to reward financial independence‚Äînot penalize it.

This is about expanding opportunity and making sure our safety net actually supports those it was designed to help.

üö®REP. ROY STATEMENT PRAISING LAW ENFORCEMENT FOR APPREHENDING TREN DE ARAGUA GANG MEMBERS IN HAYS COUNTY, TEXAS:

‚ÄúThe Biden Administration‚Äôs open-border policies, led by impeached former Department of Homeland Security (DHS) Secretary Alejandro Mayorkas, brought a historic number of criminal aliens and dangerous actors into our communities.  Texans ‚Äì including those in TX21 ‚Äì have suffered as a direct result, from dozens of fentanyl related deaths to human trafficking, and now an enormous gang operation. The Venezuela-based prison gang Tren de Aragua (TdA) - among the worst groups that have infiltrated the nation - was operating right in the heart of suburban Austin in Hays County, Texas, where I call home.

I commend the Hays County Sheriff's Office, the San Antonio Police Department (SAPD), the Texas Department of Public Safety (TDPS), U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), and the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) for apprehending these foreign gang members from our streets. The people of Texas' 21 Congressional district ‚Äì and the nation ‚Äì are safer thanks to the teamwork of these agencies.

While South American gangs engage in murder, extortion, human trafficking, and terrorism - activist judges and radical progressive Democrats continue to impede the President and Republican leaders from removing these criminals from the United States.  There should be unanimity of purpose among all our nation‚Äôs leaders to bolster enforcement efforts against all illegal aliens, criminal gangs, and cartels until every last member is incarcerated and deported.  I look forward to working with my colleagues and members of law enforcement to ensure this happens, as well as working to codify the Trump Administration‚Äôs efforts to label these evil actors as the rightful terrorists they are ‚Äì legislation I first introduced in in 2019.‚Äù

Name: Elfreth, Sarah
text:
Yesterday, Secretary Linda McMahon invited House Members to the Department of Education to discuss the future of the Department. She was the first Cabinet member to extend an invitation like this, and I‚Äôm grateful for the opportunity to actually discuss our policy differences and share the real concerns of our communities.¬†

However, I remain deeply concerned about the future of critical services for students with disabilities, early childhood education programs, and civil rights protections for our most vulnerable children. The Department still has not articulated a plan on how they intend to continue these critical services. While I am encouraged by the Secretary‚Äôs outreach, we risk a generation of students being left behind without these important safety net programs.¬†

Congress created the Department of Education. We can and should have thorough policy debates about how to best deliver services and protections for children, but the President does not have the power to dismantle the Department. House Democrats will continue to fight for a Department of Education that best serves our students and school communities, and as a member of Team Maryland, I am fighting for the full funding for our Maryland schools to ensure every child has the chance to thrive.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Real environmental progress is driven through sustained leadership, trusted partnerships, and a shared results-driven vision.
 
Since coming to Congress, I‚Äôve worked closely with my friends at the @LCVoters to turn our shared priorities into real outcomes. Together, we helped pass the Great American Outdoors Act‚Äîmy landmark legislation that permanently funded the Land and Water Conservation Fund and addressed long-overdue maintenance in our national parks.
 
Now, we‚Äôre building on that momentum by focusing on one of our region‚Äôs most critical natural resources: the Delaware River Basin. In February, I introduced the Delaware River Basin Restoration Program Reauthorization Act of 2025 to extend a proven federal initiative that protects clean water, strengthens local economies, and safeguards the long-term health of our communities. Every federal dollar invested yields exponential returns‚Äîrestoring ecosystems, creating jobs, and building climate resilience throughout the region.
 
Thank you to Senior Vice President, Tiernan Sittenfeld, our very own Tim Hayes of Dublin, and the entire LCV team for your tireless advocacy‚ÄîI look forward to continuing our work together to deliver lasting progress for our community.

Name: Miller, Mary E.
text:
BREAKING: Rep. Miller Introduces the Love Them Both Act to Prevent Abortion Coverage Under the Pregnant Workers Fairness Act 

WASHINGTON, D.C. ‚Äî Today, Congresswoman Mary Miller (IL-15) introduced the Love Them Both Act. The legislation seeks to block the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) and the Office of Congressional Workplace Rights from interpreting the Pregnant Workers Fairness Act to include coverage for abortions or related services.  

"The Pregnant Workers Fairness Act was meant to support new mothers and their children‚Äînot fund the destruction of innocent life," said Congresswoman Mary Miller. "Allowing abortion under this law directly contradicts its purpose. My bill will restore its original intent, protect unborn babies, and stand for the sanctity of life."  

"The Biden administration's radical expansion of the Pregnant Workers Fairness Act has twisted a law meant to protect expectant mothers into a tool forcing employers to facilitate abortions, directly contradicting its original intent to support women who choose to carry their pregnancies to term. I'm proud to support Rep. Mary Miller's Love Them Both Act, which stops this regulatory overreach by ensuring pregnancy accommodations support life, not end it, while ensuring the PWFA returns to its intended purpose of helping pregnant workers continue working safely as they prepare for childbirth. No one should be forced to choose between their conscience and complying with federal law. This legislation accomplishes just that," said @RepublicanStudy Chairman @RepPfluger.  

This legislation is also supported by the @EagleForum, @FRCdc, @approject, @Moms4Liberty, and @sbaprolife.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share remarkable stories from across our district of people who reflect the highest ideals of service, character, and devotion to others. Today, we honor one such man: a true hometown hero, Edward C. Wallace, whom we sadly lost last week. Ed was a proud Marine, police officer, and, above all, a man whose life was rooted in unwavering commitment‚Äîto country, community, and family.
 
Raised in Croydon and a resident of Levittown for over 45 years, Ed made every place he touched better. Humble in presence yet profound in impact, he lived with sincerity, strength, and a heart for service. As a young man, Ed answered his country‚Äôs call, enlisting in the @USMC and serving with distinction in the Vietnam War. He rose to the rank of Sergeant and received numerous military honors‚Äîincluding the Vietnam Service Medal with Two Stars, the National Defense Service Medal, the Republic of Vietnam Cross of Gallantry, and the Rifle Expert Badge.
 
After returning home, Ed continued to serve‚Äîspending over two decades with the @BristolTwpPD and later with the Tullytown Police. For Ed, service wasn‚Äôt a duty. It was who he was.

A proud Irish-American and member of the Ancient Order of Hibernians, Ed honored his heritage through fellowship and tradition. Later in life, he taught himself to play the bagpipes‚Äîan act of reverence he used to honor others during parades, funerals, and ceremonies. Through music, as in life, Ed served with quiet dignity and deep respect.
 
Just a few weeks ago, I had the profound honor of spending time with Ed and witnessing the presentation of his Quilt of Valor‚Äîa national expression of gratitude for those who have borne the burdens of war. As the quilt was laid upon him, it was clear we weren‚Äôt just honoring his service‚Äîbut the spirit in which he lived: selflessly, humbly, and with enduring grace.
 
To his beloved wife Sharon, his children, grandchildren, and all who knew him‚Äîour community grieves with you. We are forever grateful for Ed‚Äôs life, service, and enduring example.

May God bless the memory of Ed Wallace‚Äîa patriot, a protector, and a true hometown hero.

Name: Budzinski, Nikki
text:
Let's talk about tariffs...

For too long, bad trade deals have squeezed the middle class, manufacturing, and damaged our national security.¬†I believe tariffs are an important tool to support American workers, and when used strategically to fight cheap steel from China, tariffs can be critical in protecting our domestic industry.

But what President Donald Trump has done is reckless.

Instead of using a scalpel to strengthen our workforce, the President has imposed universal tariffs on all imports including on our closest trading partners. 

For the farmers in Central and Southern Illinois, this is a direct hit to their livelihoods. Tariffs drive up the cost of imported goods, from machinery to feed, and make it harder to sell crops overseas, putting their operations in jeopardy.

Now, China has retaliated, and the stock market is crashing. While people's savings plummet and they look for reassurance, the President is golfing. It's unacceptable.

Congress has a role to play here. I am ready to work with the President to negotiate stronger trade agreements that prioritize our workers, rather than strain our economy. By heeding advice from members and their districts, we can find a path forward that will LOWER costs for folks, not make it even harder to afford everyday essentials.

It‚Äôs time for smarter, effective trade policies that benefit every American.

Name: Lee, Mike
text:
This week I introduced the Stopping Harmful Incidents to Enforce Lawful Drone Use (SHIELD-U) Act and the Drone Integration and Zoning Act.
¬†
These bills equip state and local law enforcement with the authority needed to protect their citizens, communities, and airports from drone threats.

The current regulatory environment stifles state and local governments‚Äô ability to mitigate drone threats. The FAA currently regulates ‚Äúnavigable airspace‚Äù which is defined as ‚Äúabove the minimum altitudes of flight‚Äù which is typically 500 ft. However, the FAA has taken some liberties in recent years and stated that minimum altitude of flight for drones is above a blade of grass.¬†

Right now, Congress has exclusively granted limited authority to detect and takedown a drone only to the Department of Defense, Department of Homeland Security, Department of Justice, and Department of Energy. 

According to a Blue Ribbon Task Force Report commissioned by the Association for Unmanned Vehicle Systems International (AUVSI) and Airports Council International-North America (ACI-NA), one challenge in meeting current drone threats is the federal government‚Äôs lack of human resources or capital to invest in and operate counter drone technology at airports. 

When considered beyond an airport environment, the challenge becomes even greater, because federal law does not permit state or local law enforcement to take action.¬†

The SHIELD-U and Drone Integration and Zoning Acts provide essential tools for state and local law enforcement to address the danger of drones used against Americans that federal regulations have failed to adequately manage. 

By empowering local authorities, these bills ensure that communities and airports have the resources needed to safeguard their citizens and infrastructure from potential harm. 

With the increasing prevalence of drone-related incidents, it is vital to enable local enforcement to act swiftly and effectively in protecting public safety.

Catholic Social Services is far more than a provider of care‚Äîit is a pillar of strength for individuals and families facing some of life‚Äôs most difficult challenges. Their work is rooted in faith and guided by the belief that every person deserves dignity, respect, and hope.
 
As someone raised in the Catholic Church, I hold those values close. They‚Äôve shaped my life and continue to guide my work in Congress‚Äîwhere I remain committed to ensuring that organizations like CHS are recognized and supported, so they can continue expanding their reach and deepening their impact.

Name: Murkowski, Lisa
text:
Early this morning, I voted for the Senate budget resolution. I support the extension of President Trump‚Äôs tax cuts and look forward to a reconciliation measure that will boost Alaska‚Äôs resource production. There are serious shortcomings within this resolution that gave me considerable pause, but overall, I recognize this is the start of a process, not the end. 
 
The resolution‚Äôs shortcomings include the adoption of a current policy baseline, a requirement for the Senate to increase the debt ceiling by $5 trillion, the setting of a path that will result in more than $50 trillion in federal debt within a decade, and a reconciliation instruction to a House committee that would require significant cuts to Medicaid. I supported an amendment to strike that instruction during our late-night vote series, but unfortunately, it fell short.  
 
As we turn next to the budget reconciliation process, I will push for a bill that keeps tax rates low, strengthens our economy and our security, and facilitates resource production in Alaska while avoiding harmful cuts to health coverage and the worsening of our fiscal situation. If the final bill falls short on any of those fronts, I would be unable to support its passage.

Name: Johnson, Mike
text:
Today, the Senate passed its version of the budget resolution, and is sending it to the House for consideration. 

Getting the two chambers together will allow us to finally begin the most important phase of this process: drafting the reconciliation bill that will deliver on President Trump‚Äôs agenda and our promises to the American people.

There are several key things to remember as we move forward:

The budget resolution is not the law itself, but only the necessary kickoff for reconciliation to begin.

The Senate amendment as passed makes NO CHANGES to the House reconciliation instructions that we passed weeks ago. Although the Senate chose to take a different approach on its instructions, the amended resolution in NO WAY prevents us from achieving our goals in the final reconciliation bill.

We have and will continue to make it clear in all discussions with the Senate and the White House that‚Äîin order to secure House passage‚Äîthe final reconciliation bill must include historic spending reductions while protecting essential programs.

After close consultation with President Trump and Majority Leader Thune, we all agree that the ‚ÄúOne Big Beautiful Bill‚Äù must be drafted using a collaborative process that results in a single product that can be passed by both chambers and signed into law. We have made it clear the House will NOT accept nor participate in an ‚Äúus versus them‚Äù process resulting in a take-it-or-leave-it proposition from the Senate.

As soon as we pass the final budget resolution, our House and Senate committees will begin preparing together their respective titles of the reconciliation bill to be marked up in the next work period. As always, this will involve input from all Members and will keep us on track to send a bill to the President‚Äôs desk by Memorial Day.

Time is of the essence.

Roberto Clemente was a humanitarian, social justice trailblazer, and tireless advocate for the rights of Black and Latino communities. His legacy extends beyond the baseball field and continues to inspire countless fans and players alike.

As a player, Clemente was unrivaled in right field and no other name in history commands more respect than his in Latin American baseball circles.

He played in 15 All-Star Games while winning 12 Gold Glove awards, four batting titles and the 1966 National League MVP‚Äî while playing his entire career with the Pirates from 1955-72.¬†

It is deeply disappointing that the¬†Pittsburgh Pirates franchise¬†has chosen to remove a logo in his honor from the stadium, and I hope they will reconsider this decision and return the tribute to the MLB legend back at PNC Park.

On #ThisDayInHistory in 1922, the teapot dome scandal began.

After President Warren G. Harding transferred control of federal oil reserves from the Navy to the Department of the Interior, Interior Secretary Albert Fall secretly leased oil-rich lands to Harry Sinclair and Edward Doheny in exchange for large sums of money from both men. 

Fall became the first U.S. cabinet member to be imprisoned for corruption. Sinclair served jail time for contempt of court. President Harding was not directly involved but was affected by the scandal before his death.

These cuts aren‚Äôt just bureaucratic ‚Äì they‚Äôre dangerous. This administration is crippling our response to public health threats, weakening the CDC, CMS, FDA, and more, and unraveling the infrastructure we need in a crisis.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
A moving, humbling, and truly special day in our nation‚Äôs capital as we welcomed our hero veterans on this year‚Äôs Bucks County Tour of Honor.

Each year, the Tour of Honor travels from Bucks to D.C., where our veterans spend a day of fellowship and reflection‚Äîvisiting memorials, honoring fallen comrades, and celebrating the nation they served with courage and pride.

What made this year especially meaningful for me was having my dad, Jim Fitzpatrick, a proud Korean War veteran, by my side. Sharing this experience with him‚Äîamong our fellow hometown heroes‚Äîwas something I‚Äôll carry with me forever.

One of the most touching sights was seeing local students lining the route with flags and handmade signs, thanking our heroes who have given so much‚Äîit made the day even more special for everyone involved.

Grateful as always to Tour of Honor President Joe Szafran, the @BensalemSchools Marine Corps JROTC, Senior Marine Instructor Colonel John Church, the outstanding Bensalem JROTC Cadets, @parxcasino, and all who helped make this unforgettable tribute possible.

To all our veterans‚Äîyour service shaped our nation, your sacrifice inspires us all, and your legacy will never be forgotten. Today and every day, we thank you.

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
I want to take a moment to refute some of the outright lies being spread about what‚Äôs going on at the VA. 

Let‚Äôs be clear: What is happening now is not about cutting care. It is about reforming a bloated bureaucracy that has protected underperforming employees for years, often at the expense of veterans. The VA has been on the Government Accountability Office‚Äôs high-risk list since 2015. That means for nearly a decade, independent watchdogs have flagged serious, systemic failures in patient safety, access to care, staffing, and infrastructure. 

Despite the propaganda of the usual people who just parrot what they are told, the number of job reductions is not 84,000. To date, only 2,400 jobs have been cut, 0.005% of the total VA headcount, and all were probationary employees in non-critical positions such as PR, interior design, and DEI. 

The VA is going through a process to find ways to improve care and benefits for veterans. All mission-critical providers such as doctors, nurses, or claims processors are EXEMPT from cuts. To add to that, supervisors have the opportunity to request that their employees be exempted from hiring freezes and probationary removal.

The last four years have shown that higher headcounts do not equate with better outcomes. Under the Biden administration, 52,000 additional employees were brought into the VA, bringing the total staff headcount to 470,000. Yet the average wait times for various services increased as the agency grew. 

From 2021 to 2024:
- Wait times for primary care grew from 15 days to 24 days ‚Äî a 60% increase
- Wait times for mental health care grew from 14 days to 20 days ‚Äî a 42% increase
- Wait times for specialty care grew from 24 days to 38 days ‚Äî a 58% increase
- Additionally, the disability claims backlog increased.

More money and more people did not translate to better care for our veterans. It just made the system bigger, slower, and harder to navigate. 

Veterans are not asking for a larger VA bureaucracy. They are asking for a VA that actually works. As your Congressman, I‚Äôm committed to delivering for our veterans and ensuring that they receive the care they deserve. That means modernizing outdated systems, reducing inefficiency, and focusing on achieving results instead of growing headcounts.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
This afternoon, I met with Asad Malik of @PAKPAC‚Äîa courageous advocate for freedom, democracy, and the rule of law in Pakistan.

He spoke not just of politics, but of people‚Äîfamilies enduring censorship, persecution, and fear. These are not abstract issues. They are the lived realities of those who still believe in the promise of democracy, even when it comes at great personal cost.

America has always stood with those who stand for liberty. That must never change. Our strength as a nation isn‚Äôt just in our power‚Äîbut in our principles.

We must continue building a strategic partnership with Pakistan, one rooted in shared democratic values and a clear commitment to human rights. When we stand with those who fight for freedom, we reaffirm what it means to be a leader on the world stage.

My deepest thanks to Asad and the entire PAKPAC team for your leadership and reminding us that the cause of freedom is never far from home‚Äîand always worth defending.
